bc\", there is no substring that does not occur in any other string.\n- For the string \"bcd\", there is no substring that does not occur in any other string.\n- For the string \"abcd\", the shortest substring that does not occur in any other string is \"abcd\".\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `n == arr.length`\n\n- `2 <= n <= 100`\n\n- `1 <= arr[i].length <= 20`\n\n- `arr[i]` consists only of lowercase English letters.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/shortest-uncommon-substring-in-an-array/","problemName":"Shortest Uncommon Substring in an Array","problemNumber":3076,"problemSlug":"shortest-uncommon-substring-in-an-array","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":3076,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Dynamic Programming","Prefix Sum"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an array of integers `nums` with length `n`, and a positive **odd** integer `k`.\n\nSelect exactly **`k`** disjoint [subarrays](leetcode-keyword) **`sub1, sub2, ..., subk`** from `nums` such that the last element of `subi` appears before the first element of `sub{i+1}` for all `1 <= i <= k-1`. The goal is to maximize their combined strength.\n\nThe strength of the selected subarrays is defined as:\n\n`strength = k * sum(sub1)- (k - 1) * sum(sub2) + (k - 2) * sum(sub3) - ... - 2 * sum(sub{k-1}) + sum(subk)`\n\nwhere **`sum(subi)`** is the sum of the elements in the `i`-th subarray.\n\nReturn the **maximum** possible strength that can be obtained from selecting exactly **`k`** disjoint subarrays from `nums`.\n\n**Note** that the chosen subarrays **don't** need to cover the entire array.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [1,2,3,-1,2], k = 3\n\n**Output:** 22\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe best possible way to select 3 subarrays is: nums[0..2], nums[3..3], and nums[4..4]. The strength is calculated as follows:\n\n`strength = 3 * (1 + 2 + 3) - 2 * (-1) + 2 = 22`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [12,-2,-2,-2,-2], k = 5\n\n**Output:** 64\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe only possible way to select 5 disjoint subarrays is: nums[0..0], nums[1..1], nums[2..2], nums[3..3], and nums[4..4]. The strength is calculated as follows:\n\n`strength = 5 * 12 - 4 * (-2) + 3 * (-2) - 2 * (-2) + (-2) = 64`\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [-1,-2,-3], k = 1\n\n**Output:** -1\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe best possible way to select 1 subarray is: nums[0..0]. The strength is -1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁹ <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`\n\n- `1 <= k <= n`\n\n- `1 <= n * k <= 10⁶`\n\n- `k` is odd.","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Dynamic Programming","Prefix Sum"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Hard","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given an array of integers `nums` with length `n`, and a positive **odd** integer `k`.\n\nSelect exactly **`k`** disjoint [subarrays](leetcode-keyword) **`sub1, sub2, ..., subk`** from `nums` such that the last element of `subi` appears before the first element of `sub{i+1}` for all `1 <= i <= k-1`. The goal is to maximize their combined strength.\n\nThe strength of the selected subarrays is defined as:\n\n`strength = k * sum(sub1)- (k - 1) * sum(sub2) + (k - 2) * sum(sub3) - ... - 2 * sum(sub{k-1}) + sum(subk)`\n\nwhere **`sum(subi)`** is the sum of the elements in the `i`-th subarray.\n\nReturn the **maximum** possible strength that can be obtained from selecting exactly **`k`** disjoint subarrays from `nums`.\n\n**Note** that the chosen subarrays **don't** need to cover the entire array.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [1,2,3,-1,2], k = 3\n\n**Output:** 22\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe best possible way to select 3 subarrays is: nums[0..2], nums[3..3], and nums[4..4]. The strength is calculated as follows:\n\n`strength = 3 * (1 + 2 + 3) - 2 * (-1) + 2 = 22`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [12,-2,-2,-2,-2], k = 5\n\n**Output:** 64\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe only possible way to select 5 disjoint subarrays is: nums[0..0], nums[1..1], nums[2..2], nums[3..3], and nums[4..4]. The strength is calculated as follows:\n\n`strength = 5 * 12 - 4 * (-2) + 3 * (-2) - 2 * (-2) + (-2) = 64`\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [-1,-2,-3], k = 1\n\n**Output:** -1\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe best possible way to select 1 subarray is: nums[0..0]. The strength is -1.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n <= 10⁴`\n\n- `-10⁹ <= nums[i] <= 10⁹`\n\n- `1 <= k <= n`\n\n- `1 <= n * k <= 10⁶`\n\n- `k` is odd.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-strength-of-k-disjoint-subarrays/","problemName":"Maximum Strength of K Disjoint Subarrays","problemNumber":3077,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an array of integers `nums` with length `n`, and a positive **odd** integer `k`.\n\nSelect exactly **`k`** disjoint [subarrays](leetcode-keyword) **`sub1, sub2, ..., subk`** from `nums` such that the last element of `subi` appears before the first element of `sub{i+1}` for all `1 <= i <= k-1`. The goal is to maximize their combined strength.\n\nThe strength of the selected subarrays is defined as:\n\n`strength = k * sum(sub1)- (k - 1) * sum(sub2) + (k - 2) * sum(sub3) - ... - 2 * sum(sub{k-1}) + sum(subk)`\n\nwhere **`sum(subi)`** is the sum of the elements in the `i`-th subarray.\n\nReturn the **maximum** possible strength that can be obtained from selecting exactly **`k`** disjoint subarrays from `nums`.\n\n**Note** that the chosen subarrays **don't** need to cover the entire array.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [1,2,3,-1,2], k = 3\n\n**Output:** 22\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nThe best possible way to select 3 subarrays is: nums[0..2], nums[3..3], and nums[4..4]. The strength is calculated as follows:\n\n`strength = 3 * (1 + 2 + 3) - 2 * (-1) + 2 = 22`\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** nums = [12,-2,-2,-2,-2], k = 5\n\n*